<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="963" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[113,751,671,1397]" pageId="31" pageNumber="963">
<bibRefCitation author="Sweet, M. H." box="[140,281,701,725]" editor="Schaefer, C. W." journalOrPublisher="Thomas Say Publications in Entomology, Entomological Society of America, Lanham, MD, USA" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" refId="ref32696" refString="Sweet, M. H., 1996. Comparative external anatomy of the pregenital abdomen of the Hemiptera. In: Schaefer, C. W. (Ed.), Studies on Hemipteran Phylogeny. Thomas Say Publications in Entomology, Entomological Society of America, Lanham, MD, USA." title="Comparative external anatomy of the pregenital abdomen of the Hemiptera" type="book" volumeTitle="Studies on Hemipteran Phylogeny" year="1996">Sweet (1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Sweet, M. H." box="[296,351,701,725]" editor="Rabitsch, W." journalOrPublisher="Denisia" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" pagination="225 - 248" part="19" refId="ref32751" refString="Sweet, M. H., 2006. Justification for the Aradimorpha as an infraorder of the suborder Heteroptera (Hemiptera, Prosorrhyncha) with special reference to the pregenital abdominal structure. In: Rabitsch, W. (Ed.): Hug the Bug-For Love of True Bugs. Festschrift zum 70 Geburtstag von Ernst Heiss., Denisia 19, 225 - 248." title="Justification for the Aradimorpha as an infraorder of the suborder Heteroptera (Hemiptera, Prosorrhyncha) with special reference to the pregenital abdominal structure" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Hug the Bug-For Love of True Bugs. Festschrift zum 70 Geburtstag von Ernst Heiss" year="2006">2006</bibRefCitation>
) argued that the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Henry" baseAuthorityYear="1997" box="[559,664,701,725]" class="Insecta" family="Aradidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Aradidae</taxonomicName>
should be treated as a separate infraorder, Aradimorpha (originally Aradomorpha), because members of the
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[113,751,671,1397]" pageId="31" pageNumber="963">
group ‘‘have a more plesiomorphous abdominal structure, than the Leptopodomorpha + 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" infraOrder="Pentatomomorpha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="974" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="infraOrder">Pentatomomorpha</taxonomicName>
, and possess unique apomorphies’’ (
<bibRefCitation author="Sweet, M. H." editor="Schaefer, C. W." journalOrPublisher="Thomas Say Publications in Entomology, Entomological Society of America, Lanham, MD, USA" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" refId="ref32696" refString="Sweet, M. H., 1996. Comparative external anatomy of the pregenital abdomen of the Hemiptera. In: Schaefer, C. W. (Ed.), Studies on Hemipteran Phylogeny. Thomas Say Publications in Entomology, Entomological Society of America, Lanham, MD, USA." title="Comparative external anatomy of the pregenital abdomen of the Hemiptera" type="book" volumeTitle="Studies on Hemipteran Phylogeny" year="1996">Sweet, 1996</bibRefCitation>
). This viewpoint has not been widely adopted in the literature on heteropteran classification, possibly because only a few workers have devoted effort to dealing with this particular subject during the intervening period (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Cassis, G. &amp; Gross, G. F." bookContentInfo="737 pp." box="[369,674,1006,1030]" editor="Houston, W. W. K. &amp; Wells, A." journalOrPublisher="Melbourne, Australia, Vol. 27.3 B" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" refId="ref28008" refString="Cassis, G., Gross, G. F., 2002. Hemiptera- Heteroptera (Pentatomomorpha). In: Houston, W. W. K., Wells, A. (Eds.), Zoological Catalog of Australia. CSIRO Publishing, B. Melbourne, Australia, Vol. 27.3 B, xiv + 737 pp." title="Hemiptera- Heteroptera (Pentatomomorpha)" type="book" volumeTitle="Zoological Catalog of Australia. CSIRO Publishing, B" year="2002">Cassis and Gross, 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Our evidence offers no support for Sweet̕s (1996) theory, but rather corroborates the theory that the Aradoidea belong to the Geocorisae. As is the case for the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schuh and Stys" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[113,287,1129,1153]" class="Insecta" infraOrder="Cimicomorpha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="infraOrder">Cimicomorpha</taxonomicName>
, our sample for the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Henry" baseAuthorityYear="1997" box="[543,649,1129,1153]" class="Insecta" family="Aradidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Aradidae</taxonomicName>
is small and does not offer strong evidence for placement of the Aradoidea within the Geocorisae. It is nonetheless largely concordant with that of 
<bibRefCitation author="Wheeler, W. C. &amp; Schuh, R. T. &amp; Bang, R." box="[503,751,1220,1244]" journalOrPublisher="Entomol. Scand." pageId="31" pageNumber="963" pagination="121 - 137" part="24" refId="ref33056" refString="Wheeler, W. C., Schuh, R. T., Bang, R., 1993. Cladistic relationships among higher groups of Heteroptera: congruence between morphological and molecular data sets. Entomol. Scand. 24, 121 - 137." title="Cladistic relationships among higher groups of Heteroptera: congruence between morphological and molecular data sets" type="journal article" year="1993">Wheeler et al. (1993)</bibRefCitation>
in placing the Aradoidea as the sister group of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonnemaison" authorityYear="1822" box="[113,261,1281,1305]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Trichophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="963" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trichophora</taxonomicName>
. Astronger test of this theory will require analysis of a much larger taxon sample for the Aradoidea in conjunction with a broader sample from the Geocorisae and Leptopodomorpha.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
